          "body": "The sentence in verse 8 is the most personal expression of divine opposition in the chapter: *'Behold, I, even I, am against you'*. The emphatic doubling of the first-person pronoun (*hineni gam ani elayikh*) removes every mediating cushion. God is not sending an army, not dispatching angels, not permitting an enemy — He Himself is the adversary of His own city. The verdict executes in three movements that mirror the sign-act precisely: plague and famine inside the walls (the burned hair), the sword around the city (the struck hair), and scattering to every wind with a sword behind them (the scattered hair). Verse 10's horror — 'fathers will eat their sons among you, and sons will eat their fathers' — is not rhetorical excess but the literal fulfillment of the covenant curse of Deuteronomy 28:53-57 and Leviticus 26:29, documented historically in Lamentations 2:20 and 4:10 during the 586 BC siege. The curse-list of Torah has become Ezekiel's oracle. Douglas Stuart, writing on prophetic judgment oracles, notes that the vast majority of prophetic threats are 'unoriginal' in the strictest sense — they are drawn directly from the covenant curses of Leviticus 26 and Deuteronomy 27-28, which Israel had already formally accepted. The judgment is not arbitrary; it is precisely the punishment Israel covenanted to receive if it walked in this way."
