    "intro": "Interpretation asks what the text means — moving from observation to the author's intent in its original covenantal and canonical context. Ezekiel 5 is not primarily a historical prediction of the 586 BC destruction, though it is that. It is a theological exposition of why unprecedented judgment falls on the most privileged people in the ancient world, and what that judgment is designed to accomplish. The movements below trace the chapter's argument from sign-act to verdict to purpose, drawing on the covenant-curse background, the prophetic lawsuit tradition, and Ezekiel's signature recognition formula.",
