        "excerpt": "Take a sharp sword; take and use it as a barber's razor on your head and beard. Then take scales for weighing and divide the hair.",
        "body": "Ezekiel's sign-acts are not visual aids appended to verbal messages — they are the message in another medium. In ancient Near Eastern prophetic practice, the enacted word carried the same revelatory authority as the spoken word; in some traditions, the act was believed to initiate or guarantee the event it portrayed. Ezekiel performs the razor-and-hair sign under divine command (*laqach*, 'take,' appears four times in vv. 1-4, each repetition a new directive), and the precision of the act is its meaning: scales are used to weigh the hair into exact thirds. Nothing is left to chance, nothing is disproportionate — the judgment is measured, not excessive.\n\nThe shaving of head and beard in the ancient Near East was the physical vocabulary of mourning, defeat, and humiliation. Isaiah 7:20 uses the very same imagery — God hiring a razor from across the Euphrates (Assyria) to shave Judah's head and beard — to predict the Assyrian campaign. Ezekiel reconfigures the image: here, the prophet himself is shaved, making his body the site of the prophecy. The identification between the prophet's person and the city's fate is total. This is what Daniel Block (NICOT on Ezekiel) calls 'sympathetic representation' — the prophet does not merely announce Jerusalem's fate from a safe distance; he enacts it on his own body.\n\nThe three fates of the hair map onto the three fates of the population with perfect precision: fire in the city's center (vv. 2, 12 — plague and famine), sword around the city (vv. 2, 12 — military slaughter), scattering to the wind (vv. 2, 10, 12 — exile and diaspora). The remnant-strands bound in the robe (v. 3) suggest that God preserves a minimal remainder — a thread of hope in the otherwise unrelieved darkness. But even those strands face further fire (v. 4), with the fire spreading from them to all Israel. The remnant is not immune; it is merely not annihilated. The theology of the remnant in Ezekiel is not comfortable — it is provisional, tested, and refining.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Cherev* (sword) in v.1 is the barber's blade; in v.2 it is the military weapon — the same lemma bridges the sign and its referent. *Mozen* (scales, v.1) is the standard balance-scale used in commerce; its use for measuring hair intensifies the sense of cold juridical precision. *Shelishi* (one-third) occurs three times in v.2 alone, establishing the tripartite structure that governs the entire chapter."
