        "excerpt": "This is Jerusalem; I have set her at the center of the nations, with lands around her. But she has rebelled against My ordinances more wickedly than the nations.",
        "body": "The chapter's interpretive key is announced in its first oracle-word: 'I have set her at the center of the nations.' This is not a claim about physical geography alone, though ancient Near Eastern maps (notably the Babylonian 'Imago Mundi' tablet) often placed significant cities at the center of their world-diagrams. The theological claim is that God's own sovereign placement of Jerusalem was purposive — she was the hub of divine revelation, the city from which Torah would go forth (Isaiah 2:3; Micah 4:2). The greater the calling, the greater the accountability.\n\nThe accusation in verse 6 is therefore not merely moral failure but covenantal inversion. Jerusalem did not simply fall short of God's standard — she fell below the standard maintained by the surrounding pagan nations. The nations had no Sinai covenant, no written Torah, no prophets, no temple-presence; and yet Ezekiel charges that Jerusalem failed to observe even 'the ordinances of the nations which surround you' (5:7). This is the most extreme possible formulation of covenantal failure: the most privileged people became the least faithful. The logic is the logic of Luke 12:48 — 'to whom much is given, from him much will be required' — applied with full force to national covenant.\n\nThe comparative structure of vv. 6-7 ('more wickedly than the nations,' 'more than the lands') is not hyperbole — it is a deliberate legal brief establishing that the sentence in v. 8 is proportional. Commentators from Calvin (*Commentaries on Ezekiel*) to Iain Duguid (*Ezekiel*, NIV Application Commentary) note that this accusation addresses not merely pagans who never knew God, but covenant people who had been given what no other people had been given. The contrast with the nations, repeated seven times through the oracle via *saviv* and *goy*, is Ezekiel's way of making the scandal of Jerusalem's failure maximally visible.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Marah* (rebelled, v.6) — the root of bitter, willful defiance, used of Israel's Meribah-rebellion and throughout the prophets for covenant apostasy. *Mishpat* (ordinances) carries both the sense of God's legal decisions *given* to Israel (the gift) and the judicial sentences He now *executes* (the judgment) — the same word does double duty in the chapter, which is itself part of Ezekiel's theological irony."
