        "body": "The verdict of verse 8 is unlike any divine declaration elsewhere in the Old Testament in its direct, doubled first-person intensity: *hineni gam ani elayikh* — 'Behold, I, also I, am against you.' The particle *gam ani* ('also I, even I') is emphatic addition: as if to say, not merely the nations, not merely circumstances, not merely your own sins — I myself, personally, am now your adversary. This is the covenantal curse of Leviticus 26:17 — 'I will set My face against you' — extended to its ultimate expression. God who stood between Israel and her enemies now stands as her enemy.\n\nThe judgment is described as unprecedented in verse 9: 'I will do among you what I have not done, and the like of which I will never do again.' This double temporal frame — nothing before it, nothing after — places the fall of Jerusalem in a singular category. Jesus cites this same language in Matthew 24:21 ('there will be great tribulation, such as has not occurred since the beginning of the world until now, nor ever will') in the context of Jerusalem's AD 70 destruction — which, for Jesus, is both the fulfillment of Ezekiel's prophecy and a type of the end-time tribulation. The two destructions of Jerusalem (586 BC and AD 70) form a canonical pair of unprecedented covenantal judgments.\n\nVerse 10's cannibal horror is the precise fulfillment of Deuteronomy 28:53-57 and Leviticus 26:29, the covenant curse for prolonged siege conditions. This is not Ezekiel inventing new threats — it is Ezekiel announcing the execution of the curses Israel formally accepted at Sinai and Moab. Lamentations 2:20 and 4:10 confirm this actually occurred in 586 BC. Douglas Stuart's *Hosea-Jonah* (WBC) demonstrates that approximately 70% of prophetic judgment oracles are direct applications of these covenant curses. Ezekiel is not improvising — he is applying the covenant sanctions with full knowledge of their Torah origin.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Toevah* (abominations, v.9, 11) — the strongest term of cultic revulsion in the Old Testament, used primarily of idolatry and perversion. *Sheerit* (remnant, v.10) — the small portion that survives, a technical term in prophetic theology for the preserved seed of God's future purposes (cf. Isaiah 10:20-22; Micah 5:7-8). Even the remnant is scattered here — survival is not yet full restoration."
