        "body": "Verse 11 occupies a structurally unique position in the oracle: it is the only verse sealed by the divine oath formula (*chai ani*, 'as I live, declares the Lord God'), indicating that the sin here named is the pivot-point of the entire indictment. Among all Jerusalem's failures — rejected ordinances, violated statutes, moral descent below the nations — the defilement of the sanctuary (*miqdash*) is the sin that triggers the sworn oath.\n\nThe theology is precise: the sanctuary was the architectural statement of God's covenant presence — the place where heaven and earth intersected, where the Glory (*kavod*) dwelt above the cherubim. When Israel brought *shiqqutsim* (detestable idols) and *toevah* (abominations) into this space, she desecrated the very site of divine self-disclosure. Ezekiel 8 elaborates in painful detail what was happening in the temple courts: the idol of jealousy at the entrance (8:5), seventy elders burning incense to images (8:11), women weeping for Tammuz (8:14), and men bowing to the sun with their backs to the temple (8:16). What Ezekiel 5:11 announces as the trigger, Ezekiel 8 narrates as the crime.\n\nThe consequence of sanctuary defilement is stated with chilling economy: 'I will also withdraw' (*gara*), 'My eye will have no pity' (*chus*), and 'I will not spare' (*chamal*). These three clauses are the reversal of the covenant's most intimate provision — God dwelling in the midst of His people, His eye protecting them, His compassion restraining disaster. Numbers 35:34 prohibits defiling the land 'in which I dwell, for I the Lord am dwelling in the midst of the sons of Israel.' The defilement of the sanctuary is therefore not merely a religious offense but the eviction of the Landlord — who then withdraws His protection. The Shekinah glory's departure, narrated in Ezekiel 10-11, is the narrative fulfillment of 5:11's 'I will withdraw.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Miqdash* (sanctuary) — from *qadash* (to be holy, set apart). The root itself encodes the violation: what is set apart has been treated as common. *Gara* (withdraw, diminish) is the verb of God pulling back His presence — the opposite of *yashav* (to dwell among). *Chamal* (spare) is the word of tender parental compassion; its negation here is the withdrawal of exactly that tenderness."
