        "excerpt": "Thus My anger will be spent and I will satisfy My wrath on them, and I will be appeased; then they will know that I, the Lord, have spoken in My zeal.",
        "body": "The oracle's closing movement is often misread as merely amplifying the preceding threats. But verse 13 introduces a theological shift that governs the rest: 'Thus My anger will be spent and I will satisfy My wrath on them, and I will be appeased.' The verb *nacham* (be appeased, comforted, relent) in this context describes the satisfaction of divine justice — not a cooling of indifference but the completion of a purposeful action. God's wrath is not the divine equivalent of human rage; it is His holy response to covenant betrayal, and it has a teleology.\n\nThe recognition formula that follows — 'then they will know that I, the Lord, have spoken in My zeal' (5:13) — is the hermeneutical key to the entire Book of Ezekiel. Block and Greenberg both identify this formula (*yada ki ani Adonai*) as Ezekiel's central theological refrain, appearing over 70 times. The formula names the final purpose of every divine act in the book: whether judgment or restoration, the goal is that Israel and the nations come to know — not merely acknowledge but experientially recognize — who God is. The destruction of Jerusalem is not the end of the story; it is the violent removal of a false story so that the true one can be told.\n\nVerses 14-17 specify the international scope of the judgment: Jerusalem will be a 'desolation and a reproach' (5:14), a 'reproach, a reviling, a warning and an object of horror to the nations who surround you' (5:15). Four nouns of shame (*cherpah*, *geduphah*, *musar*, *meshammah*) accumulate to describe the reversal of Jerusalem's center-calling. She was placed at the center to radiate God's glory; she now radiates His judgment. The nations who were meant to see God through her witness now see God *against* her — a darker but equally valid display of His character. As Jonathan Edwards observed in his theology of divine glory: God's wrath in judgment is as much a manifestation of His perfection as His mercy in redemption. The nations will know, even through horror, that this God speaks and acts.\n\nThe triple closing formula — 'I, the Lord, have spoken' (5:13, 15, 17) — is Ezekiel's liturgical seal. In a context where the exiles might have concluded that Babylon's military success proved Marduk's superiority over Yahweh, Ezekiel insists on the contrary: the fall of Jerusalem is not evidence of God's defeat but of His word's fulfillment. The word that established the covenant at Sinai is the word now executing its sanctions, and the correspondence between the spoken threat and the historical event is precisely the ground of future faith in the spoken promise.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chemah* (wrath, fury) — from the root meaning burning heat; used of God's most intense emotional response to covenant violation (also in 5:15 ×2). *Qinah* (zeal, jealousy, 5:13) — the covenant-love that cannot tolerate rivals, the same emotion behind the second commandment's prohibition of idolatry (Exodus 20:5). God acts in *qinah* — His action is not dispassionate jurisprudence but the outpouring of a Husband's violated love for His covenant partner."
